ield_52fbc541cfb03'),(1517,420,'_curriculum_vitae','421'),(1518,420,'__curriculum_vitae','field_52fbce8765544'),(1519,420,'_alumni','0'),(1520,420,'__alumni','field_5310d6b20e086'),(1521,420,'_people_category','Graduate Students'),(1522,420,'__people_category','field_530b901b0ca70'),(1523,420,'_education','B.S. Cell Biology, University of Minnesota Duluth, 2006'),(1524,420,'__education','field_530503a0f8e71'),(1525,420,'_research_interests','I am interested in using DNA barcodes to detect species in different environments. In practice species detection can mean a number of things, including detecting prey in a predator’s stomach or residual DNA in water samples, among others.'),(1526,420,'__research_interests','field_530507cebdd0e'),(1527,420,'_research_projects','Predation plays an important role in the decline of several fishes native to the Sacramento-San Joaquin river delta. We hope to shed some light on these predator-prey interactions by identifying the stomach contents of non-native predators. Traditional stomach content studies are limited by how digested the prey are inside the gut. We can bypass this issue by identifying species by their DNA. I am developing and applying genetic (qPCR) assays to identify at-risk species in predator’s guts. This information will be important in creating a plan for management and restoration of these species.'),(1528,420,'__research_projects','field_530507efae298'),(1529,420,'_publications',''),(1530,420,'__publications','field_5305081a9bade'),(1531,423,'_edit_last','1'),(1532,423,'_edit_lock','1394645802:1'),(1533,424,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/Erickson_CV.doc'),(1534,425,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/Bjorn_erickson_profile_image.jpg'),(1535,425,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:300;s:6:\"height\";i:232;s:4:\"file\";s:40:\"2014/03/Bjorn_erickson_profile_image.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:40:\"Bjorn_erickson_profile_image-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;