er/\">Glassware Cleaner</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"dNTPs (Promega)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/dntps-promega/\">dNTPs (Promega)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1M Tris-Cl\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1m-tris-cl/\">1M Tris-Cl</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\".5M EDTA (pH 8.0)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/5m-edta-ph-8-0/\">0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1x-te-10mm-tris-1mm-edta/\">1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1X TLE (10mM Tris; 0.1mM EDTA)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1x-tle-10mm-tris-0-1mm-edta/\">1X TLE (10mM Tris; 0.1 mM EDTA)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"10X TNE\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/10x-tne/\">10X TNE</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"10X TBE “One-Shots”\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/10x-tbe-one-shots/\">10X TBE “One-Shots”</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>FujiFilm</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"FujiFilm DNA Quantification\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/fujifilm-dna-quantification/\">DNA quantification</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>ABI 3730xl Maintenance</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"3730Maintenance.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/3730Maintenance.html\">3730xl Maintenance</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"ProtKwash.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/ProtKwash.html\">Proteinase K Wash</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> Acrylamide gels</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Acrylamide.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Acrylamide.html\">Acrylamide Gel </a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"AcGelpour.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/AcGelpour.html\">Pouring</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"AcGelRun.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/AcGelRun.html\">Running</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Fluidigm</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/FLUIDIGM EP1 PROTOCOL.doc\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/FLUIDIGM%20EP1%20PROTOCOL.doc\">Fluidigm EP1 Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Illumina</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/RAD-SEQ Protocol.doc\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/RAD-SEQ%20Protocol.doc\">RAD-SEQ Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Other</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/tissuesampleprot.pdf\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/tissuesampleprot.pdf\">Tissue Sampling</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Supplies.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Supplies.html\">Ordering and Receiving Supplies</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Supplies.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Supplies.html\">PCR Tips and Tricks</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Protocols and Procedures','','inherit','closed','open','','217-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:56:50','2014-03-07 21:56:50','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/217-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(357,1,'2014-03-07 21:59:10','2014-03-07 21:59:10','<ul>\r\n	<li>Check reservoir, buffer jar &amp; polymer level before each run\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Dilute buffer to 1x before use</li>\r\n	<li>Buffer should reach the red line of the jar</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Clean surfaces, check for bubbles, leaks, and capillaries daily</li>\r\n	<li>Change waste water, rinse water, and buffer chamber weekly\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Use DI H<sub>2</sub>O for wash and refill</li>\r\n	<li>Manual Control -&gt; Autosampler -&gt; Unload tray</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Flush water trap, replenish polymer weekly</li>\r\n	<li>Reboot system weekly</li>\r\n	<li>Run Water Wash Wizard monthly</li>\r\n</ul>','3730xl General Maintenance','','publish','closed','open','','3730xl-general-maintenance','','','2014-03-07 21:59:23','2014-03-07 21:59:23','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=357',0,'page','',0),(358,1,'2014-03-07 21:59:10','2014-03-07 21:59:10','<ul>\r\n	<li>Check reservoir, buffer jar &amp; polymer level before each run\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Dilute buffer to 1x before use</li>\r\n	<li>Buffer should reach the red line of the jar</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Clean surfaces, check for bubbles, leaks, and capillaries daily</li>\r\n	<li>Change waste water, rinse water, and buffer chamber weekly\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Use DI H<sub>2</sub>O for wash and refill</li>\r\n	<li>Manual Control -&gt; Autosampler -&gt; Unload tray</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Flush water trap, replenish polymer weekly</li>\r\n	<li>Reboot system weekly</li>\r\n	<li>Run Water Wash Wizard monthly</li>\r\n</ul>','3730xl General Maintenance','','inherit','closed','open','','357-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:59:10','2014-03-07 21:59:10','',357,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/357-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(359,1,'2014-03-07 22:01:20','2014-03-07 22:01:20','<strong>Buffers &amp; Stocks</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"98% Formamide Loading Dye\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/98-formamide-loading-dye/\">Formamide Loading Dye</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Diluting 1Kb Plus Ladder with Dye\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/diluting-1kb-plus-ladder-with-dye/\">Diluting 1kb Ladder/Dye</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Gelco Fluorescein Ladder\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/gelco-fluorescein-ladder/\">Gelco Fluorescein Ladder</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Proteinase K\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/proteinase-k/\">Proteinase K</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Glassware Cleaner\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/glassware-cleaner/\">Glassware Cleaner</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"dNTPs (Promega)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/dntps-promega/\">dNTPs (Promega)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1M Tris-Cl\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1m-tris-cl/\">1M Tris-Cl</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\".5M EDTA (pH 8.0)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/5m-edta-ph-8-0/\">0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1x-te-10mm-tris-1mm-edta/\">1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1X TLE (10mM Tris; 0.1mM EDTA)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1x-tle-10mm-tris-0-1mm-edta/\">1X TLE (10mM Tris; 0.1 mM EDTA)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"10X TNE\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/10x-tne/\">10X TNE</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"10X TBE “One-Shots”\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/10x-tbe-one-shots/\">10X TBE “One-Shots”</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>FujiFilm</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"FujiFilm DNA Quantification\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/fujifilm-dna-quantification/\">DNA quantification</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>ABI 3730xl Maintenance</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"3730xl General Maintenance\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/3730xl-general-maintenance/\">3730xl Maintenance</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"ProtKwash.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/ProtKwash.html\">Proteinase K Wash</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> Acrylamide gels</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Acrylamide.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Acrylamide.html\">Acrylamide Gel </a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"AcGelpour.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/AcGelpour.html\">Pouring</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"AcGelRun.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/AcGelRun.html\">Running</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Fluidigm</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/FLUIDIGM EP1 PROTOCOL.doc\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/FLUIDIGM%20EP1%20PROTOCOL.doc\">Fluidigm EP1 Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Illumina</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/RAD-SEQ Protocol.doc\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/RAD-SEQ%20Protocol.doc\">RAD-SEQ Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Other</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/tissuesampleprot.pdf\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/tissuesampleprot.pdf\">Tissue Sampling</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Supplies.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Supplies.html\">Ordering and Receiving Supplies</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Supplies.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Supplies.html\">PCR Tips and Tricks</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Protocols and Procedures','','inherit','closed','open','','217-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 22:01:20','2014-03-07 22:01:20','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/217-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(361,1,'2014-03-10 17:29:51','2014-03-10 17:29:51','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Proteinase K Capillary Wash and Sapphire Block Wash Protocol</span></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">WARNING: Polymer and “Junk Polymer” can act as a neurotoxin. Be sure to wear gloves when handling these materials.</span></p>\r\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preparatory Steps</span></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>ProK Solution:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Check the fridge for previously made Proteinase K solution. It should be on the door in a small bottle marked “Pro K”, if the Pro K has only been used once before, go ahead and use it. If this is the second use, after you’re done, pour it down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li>New Batch: 50uL of ProK + 25mL of Water</li>\r\n	<li>ProK solution can be found in the back freezer in the white box labeled Proteinase K. Only use the purified water in the bottles on the right side of the sink.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Remove “Junk” polymer from refrigerator. Set aside to warm to room temperature.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove 28mL bottle of polymer from the refrigerator and a clean empty 7mL bottle from the back sink. Transfer polymer from the 28mL bottle into the 7mL bottle until the meniscus reaches the black line.</li>\r\n	<li>4.3730 buffer dilution: Using the red serological pipette, found in the “Sephadex and Purification” drawer, with a 25mL tip, add 15mL of 10x stock 3730 buffer, found on the door of the fridge, to a 250mL graduated cylinder. Add 135mL of HPLC water, or enough to reach the 150mL graduation.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove 3 clean trays and tops from the “Sephadex and Purification” drawer. One tray will be used for each of the following: buffer, waste, water.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Proteinase K Capillary Wash</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Minimize collection window and enter “My Computer” on the desktop\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Enter Local Disk (C:)</li>\r\n	<li>Open Applied Biosystems folder</li>\r\n	<li>Open Firmware folder</li>\r\n	<li>Open 3730calib</li>\r\n	<li>Change Syringe Injection Speed from 200 to 100</li>\r\n	<li>Change Syringe Plunger Speed from 400 to 200</li>\r\n	<li>Save</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>In the Service Console, press “Stop All” and wait for all symbols to turn from green squares to red circles. Restart the computer.</li>\r\n	<li>Windows will prompt your for username and password. Sign on as Administrator and enter password, and turn 3730 back on. Wait for the blinking yellow light to turn solid green.</li>\r\n	<li>Open Data Collection Software (Start, Programs, Applied Biosystems, Collection software) or use shortcut on desktop</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Manual Control in collection software.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Send Defined Command for: Oven</li>\r\n	<li>Command Name: Set Oven State</li>\r\n	<li>Value: On, Send</li>\r\n	<li>Command Name: Set Oven Temperature</li>\r\n	<li>Value: 60.0, Send</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Pour Proteinase K solution that you have prepared into a clean, empty polymer jar.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remove polymer jar and replace with Proteinase K solution.</li>\r\n	<li>Transfer excess polymer into “Junk Polymer” bottle.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Spatial Run Scheduler in the collection software window.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Find Spatial Protocols in lower right portion of window.</li>\r\n	<li>Protocol: SpatialFill_1</li>\r\n	<li>Click Start\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Buffer tray will return to original position, the waste tray will rinse the capillaries, water will wash the capillaries and finally, the buffer tray returns to “Active Position”</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Click Stop when “Collecting Data…” appears on the progress bar (If you are away from the machine for an extended period of time, DO NOT “Accept” the new spatial…click “Reject” and then continue with the next wash)</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat 14 more times for a total of 15 Washes (or more, if desired)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat step 7, except replace proteinase K solution with a polymer jar filled with warm HPLC grade water. This should be done for a total of 10 times to wash out any residual proteinase K solution in the capillaries. Return PK solution to the top, door shelf of the fridge, if you had to prepare the dilution. If not, pour the solution down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Go to Manual Control and return the oven state to OFF by following steps 5 b thru c.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Sapphire Block Wash</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Remove anode jar from lower block</span>, empty the contents into the waste container and replace the jar back onto the lower block.</li>\r\n	<li>(If necessary, add additional HPLC water to polymer bottle)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Instrument Status in the collection software</li>\r\n	<li>From the “Wizards” menu, select “Water Wash Wizard”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Select Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select Water Wash—wait until wash is 100% complete.</li>\r\n	<li>Click Cancel. One wash is now complete.</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat these steps two more times for a total of three washes</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>From the “Wizards” menu, select “Change Polymer Wizard”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Make sure the polymer jar has enough volume of HPLC grade water and continue.</li>\r\n	<li>Select Same Lot, Next, Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select Prime, then Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select No Bubbles, then Next\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If you do see bubbles, or you are unsure if there are any, call over Sheryl, Kerry, or Shelley. You will use the “Bubble Removal Wizard” once you reach step 15. The bubble removal wizard requires a viscous substance, like polymer, so wait until step 15.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Select No Bubbles, then Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select Fill Array, then Finish</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat these steps once more for a total of two washes</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat step 14 with “Junk Polymer” bottle in place of HPLC filled jar.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove “Junk Polymer” jar and replace with Polymer and perform “Change Polymer Wizard” as in step 14.</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Return the Syringe Injection Speed from 100 to 200 and Syringe Plunger Speed from 200 to 400 repeating steps 1-4.</span></li>\r\n	<li>Press “Tray” so you can remove the old buffer tray and replace it with a clean, new tray. Pour all liquids from trays into the waste container. <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Add the appropriate solutions so the meniscus is at the black line: buffer in the buffer tray, and water in BOTH the water and waste trays.</span> Place lids and put on “waste” septa found in the “Sephadex and Purification” drawer.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Dump the Waste tray into the waste container. The buffer and water trays can be dumped down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li>In a plastic tub soak all dirty trays in DI water.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Refill large anode jar with buffer, filling just below the red line. Make sure the anode is at least submersed in buffer. It is okay to be below the red line, just not above the line. Place the large anode jar onto the lower block. Make sure all buffer is wiped off of the top of the anode jar.</span></li>\r\n	<li>Press “Tray” again to return the buffer tray to the capillaries. Turn light off.</li>\r\n	<li>Restart the computer.</li>\r\n	<li>The machine is now ready.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Clean Up!</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Wash all empty bottles, trays, graduated cylinders, and waste septa by soaking them in DI water in large plastic container.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remember to wear gloves as the residual polymer left in some of these containers can act as a neurotoxin</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Be sure to tightly close the waste container bottle after you are finished!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNote: This protocol is for a 48-cap array, so needs to do 2 flushes per every 1 on the 96 capillary','Proteinase K Wash','','publish','closed','open','','proteinase-k-wash','','','2014-03-10 17:54:53','2014-03-10 17:54:53','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=361',0,'page','',0),(362,1,'2014-03-10 17:29:51','2014-03-10 17:29:51','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Proteinase K Capillary Wash and Sapphire Block Wash Protocol</span></h3>\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">WARNING: Polymer and “Junk Polymer” can act as a neurotoxin. Be sure to wear gloves when handling these materials.</span>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preparatory Steps</span></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>ProK Solution:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Check the fridge for previously made Proteinase K solution. It should be on the door in a small bottle marked “Pro K”, if the Pro K has only been used once before, go ahead and use it. If this is the second use, after you’re done, pour it down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li>New Batch: 50uL of ProK + 25mL of Water</li>\r\n	<li>ProK solution can be found in the back freezer in the white box labeled Proteinase K. Only use the purified water in the bottles on the right side of the sink.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Remove “Junk” polymer from refrigerator. Set aside to warm to room temperature.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove 28mL bottle of polymer from the refrigerator and a clean empty 7mL bottle from the back sink. Transfer polymer from the 28mL bottle into the 7mL bottle until the meniscus reaches the black line.</li>\r\n	<li>4.3730 buffer dilution: Using the red serological pipette, found in the “Sephadex and Purification” drawer, with a 25mL tip, add 15mL of 10x stock 3730 buffer, found on the door of the fridge, to a 250mL graduated cylinder. Add 135mL of HPLC water, or enough to reach the 150mL graduation.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove 3 clean trays and tops from the “Sephadex and Purification” drawer. One tray will be used for each of the following: buffer, waste, water.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Proteinase K Capillary Wash</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Minimize collection window and enter “My Computer” on the desktop\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Enter Local Disk (C:)</li>\r\n	<li>Open Applied Biosystems folder</li>\r\n	<li>Open Firmware folder</li>\r\n	<li>Open 3730calib</li>\r\n	<li>Change Syringe Injection Speed from 200 to 100</li>\r\n	<li>Change Syringe Plunger Speed from 400 to 200</li>\r\n	<li>Save</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>In the Service Console, press “Stop All” and wait for all symbols to turn from green squares to red circles. Restart the computer.</li>\r\n	<li>Windows will prompt your for username and password. Sign on as Administrator and enter password, and turn 3730 back on. Wait for the blinking yellow light to turn solid green.</li>\r\n	<li>Open Data Collection Software (Start, Programs, Applied Biosystems, Collection software) or use shortcut on desktop</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Manual Control in collection software.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Send Defined Command for: Oven</li>\r\n	<li>Command Name: Set Oven State</li>\r\n	<li>Value: On, Send</li>\r\n	<li>Command Name: Set Oven Temperature</li>\r\n	<li>Value: 60.0, Send</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Pour Proteinase K solution that you have prepared into a clean, empty polymer jar.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remove polymer jar and replace with Proteinase K solution.</li>\r\n	<li>Transfer excess polymer into “Junk Polymer” bottle.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Spatial Run Scheduler in the collection software window.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Find Spatial Protocols in lower right portion of window.</li>\r\n	<li>Protocol: SpatialFill_1</li>\r\n	<li>Click Start\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Buffer tray will return to original position, the waste tray will rinse the capillaries, water will wash the capillaries and finally, the buffer tray returns to “Active Position”</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Click Stop when “Collecting Data…” appears on the progress bar (If you are away from the machine for an extended period of time, DO NOT “Accept” the new spatial…click “Reject” and then continue with the next wash)</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat 14 more times for a total of 15 Washes (or more, if desired)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat step 7, except replace proteinase K solution with a polymer jar filled with warm HPLC grade water. This should be done for a total of 10 times to wash out any residual proteinase K solution in the capillaries. Return PK solution to the top, door shelf of the fridge, if you had to prepare the dilution. If not, pour the solution down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Go to Manual Control and return the oven state to OFF by following steps 5 b thru c.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Sapphire Block Wash</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Remove anode jar from lower block</span>, empty the contents into the waste container and replace the jar back onto the lower block.</li>\r\n	<li>(If necessary, add additional HPLC water to polymer bottle)</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Instrument Status in the collection software</li>\r\n	<li>From the “Wizards” menu, select “Water Wash Wizard”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Select Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select Water Wash—wait until wash is 100% complete.</li>\r\n	<li>Click Cancel. One wash is now complete.</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat these steps two more times for a total of three washes</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>From the “Wizards” menu, select “Change Polymer Wizard”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Make sure the polymer jar has enough volume of HPLC grade water and continue.</li>\r\n	<li>Select Same Lot, Next, Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select Prime, then Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select No Bubbles, then Next\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If you do see bubbles, or you are unsure if there are any, call over Sheryl, Kerry, or Shelley. You will use the “Bubble Removal Wizard” once you reach step 15. The bubble removal wizard requires a viscous substance, like polymer, so wait until step 15.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Select No Bubbles, then Next</li>\r\n	<li>Select Fill Array, then Finish</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat these steps once more for a total of two washes</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Repeat step 14 with “Junk Polymer” bottle in place of HPLC filled jar.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove “Junk Polymer” jar and replace with Polymer and perform “Change Polymer Wizard” as in step 14.</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Return the Syringe Injection Speed from 100 to 200 and Syringe Plunger Speed from 200 to 400 repeating steps 1-4.</span></li>\r\n	<li>Press “Tray” so you can remove the old buffer tray and replace it with a clean, new tray. Pour all liquids from trays into the waste container. <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Add the appropriate solutions so the meniscus is at the black line: buffer in the buffer tray, and water in BOTH the water and waste trays.</span> Place lids and put on “waste” septa found in the “Sephadex and Purification” drawer.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Dump the Waste tray into the waste container. The buffer and water trays can be dumped down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li>In a plastic tub soak all dirty trays in DI water.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Refill large anode jar with buffer, filling just below the red line. Make sure the anode is at least submersed in buffer. It is okay to be below the red line, just not above the line. Place the large anode jar onto the lower block. Make sure all buffer is wiped off of the top of the anode jar.</span></li>\r\n	<li>Press “Tray” again to return the buffer tray to the capillaries. Turn light off.</li>\r\n	<li>Restart the computer.</li>\r\n	<li>The machine is now ready.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Clean Up!</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Wash all empty bottles, trays, graduated cylinders, and waste septa by soaking them in DI water in large plastic container.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Remember to wear gloves as the residual polymer left in some of these containers can act as a neurotoxin</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Be sure to tightly close the waste container bottle after you are finished!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNote: This protocol is for a 48-cap array, so needs to do 2 flushes per every 1 on the 96 capillary','Proteinase K Wash','','inherit','closed','open','','361-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 17:29:51','2014-03-10 17:29:51','',361,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/361-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(363,1,'2014-03-10 17:33:25','2014-03-10 17:33:25','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">5% Acrylamide; 7.5M Urea</span></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Note: Urea and acrylamide are toxic, so wear gloves and avoid skin contamination</span></p>\r\n1X TBE: 250ml\r\n\r\n40% acrylamide: 62.5 mL (Biorad 40% acrylamide/bis solution 19:1 catalog#1610144)\r\n\r\nUrea: 227.29 g (Sigma U-1250/5kg)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> Mix acrylamide and TBE</li>\r\n	<li>Add urea and stir until it dissolves (at least 3 hours).</li>\r\n	<li>Note: Do not heat the solution to speed up the dissolution of urea since this will produce uric acid due to the breakdown of urea.</li>\r\n	<li>Bring to 500ml volume in graduated cylinder</li>\r\n	<li>Filter with 0.45um filter into 1L glass bottle</li>\r\n	<li>Transfer solution from glass bottles to brown plastic bottles</li>\r\n	<li>Store at 4°C in the dark.</li>\r\n</ul>','Acrylamide (Manual Gel)','','publish','closed','open','','acrylamide-manual-gel','','','2014-03-10 17:55:16','2014-03-10 17:55:16','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=363',0,'page','',0),(364,1,'2014-03-10 17:33:25','2014-03-10 17:33:25','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">5% Acrylamide; 7.5M Urea</span></h3>\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Note: Urea and acrylamide are toxic, so wear gloves and avoid skin contamination</span>\r\n\r\n1X TBE: 250ml\r\n\r\n40% acrylamide: 62.5 mL (Biorad 40% acrylamide/bis solution 19:1 catalog#1610144)\r\n\r\nUrea: 227.29 g (Sigma U-1250/5kg)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> Mix acrylamide and TBE</li>\r\n	<li>Add urea and stir until it dissolves (at least 3 hours).</li>\r\n	<li>Note: Do not heat the solution to speed up the dissolution of urea since this will produce uric acid due to the breakdown of urea.</li>\r\n	<li>Bring to 500ml volume in graduated cylinder</li>\r\n	<li>Filter with 0.45um filter into 1L glass bottle</li>\r\n	<li>Transfer solution from glass bottles to brown plastic bottles</li>\r\n	<li>Store at 4°C in the dark.</li>\r\n</ul>','Acrylamide (Manual Gel)','','inherit','closed','open','','363-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 17:33:25','2014-03-10 17:33:25','',363,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/363-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(365,1,'2014-03-10 17:47:34','2014-03-10 17:47:34','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Pouring Acrylamide Gels for Manual Run</span></h3>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Hazardous materials:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nAcrylamide: neurotoxin\r\n\r\nTEMED: corrosive\r\n\r\nFor complete information, refer to the MSDS for each substance.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PPE required:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nGloves: Nitrile\r\n\r\nEyewear\r\n\r\nLab Coat\r\n\r\nClosed toed shoes\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Precautions to observe:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nMix polyacrylamide under hood\r\n\r\nAvoid contact with skin/eyes\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;\">In case of contact:</span></strong></span>\r\n\r\nIf in contact with skin: remove clothing and use emergency shower or eye wash for 15 min\r\n\r\nCall EHS to clean up water in hallway\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;\">Procedure:</span></strong></span>\r\n\r\nPrepare plates (use the gel-pouring bench on the west side of the main lab)\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Cut bench paper large enough to cover the surface that you will be using.</li>\r\n	<li>Choose 1 short and 1 long plate per gel</li>\r\n	<li>Set plates on white, plastic tube racks.</li>\r\n	<li>Clean the inside of both plates with 95% ethanol and a Kimwipe</li>\r\n	<li>Clean with isopropanol and a kimwipe.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The plates should be completely free of smears or grease. After the isopropanol wash the glass will feel kind of slippery.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Wipe a small amount of Rain-X on the inside of the short plate ONLY.</li>\r\n	<li>Place spacers on each (long) side of the long plate.</li>\r\n	<li>Place the clean, Rain-Xed side of the short plate on top of the spacers, facing the long plate.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The bottom of the plates should be flush and spacers should be sandwiched inside the plates, aligned with the outer, long edges.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Use 2-4 binding clips to clip and hold the plates together.</li>\r\n	<li>Apply a casting boot to the bottom and sides of the plates removing clips as necessary.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Make sure the short plate is on top of the long plate and the hole to insert the syringe at the bottom of the boot is facing up.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preparation of polyacrylamide (must be done in the hood)</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>For each gel to be poured use the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>30ml 5% acrylamide (from 4 degree refrigerator)</li>\r\n	<li>90μl TEMED (in the hood)</li>\r\n	<li>90μl 10% APS (in 4 degree refrigerator)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Swirl gently in beaker.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Pouring polyacrylamide into ge</span>l\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Carefully draw ~35ml of the polyacrylamide solution into a plastic syringe avoiding air bubbles.</li>\r\n	<li>Insert syringe into the hole in the bottom of the casting boot.</li>\r\n	<li>Slowly depress plunger, allowing acrylamide to flow in between the plates.</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed until the acrylamide fills the space between the plates and begins to run out at the top of the short plate.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove syringe.</li>\r\n	<li>Plug hole in casting boot with modified pipette tip.</li>\r\n	<li>Insert comb, blunt side down, into the space at between the plates at the top of the gel.</li>\r\n	<li>Use 1-3 binding clips to secure the comb and the top of the plates together.</li>\r\n	<li>Wait ~20 minutes to allow adequate polymerization.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNotes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If you have trouble and have to discard the gel, POLYMERIZE the acrylamide first, before disposal. NEVER pour unpolymerized acrylamide down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li>Dispose of used bench paper after each use.</li>\r\n	<li>If supplies are running low, be sure to notify the ordering or stocks personnel.</li>\r\n	<li>Polymerized gels can be stored for future use by placing dampened (with water) paper towels over the top/bottom ends and covering the whole gel in saran wrap to avoid dehydration. Remove the casing boot prior to wrapping and storage.</li>\r\n</ul>','Acrylamide Gel Pour','','publish','closed','open','','acrylamide-gel-pour','','','2014-03-10 17:47:34','2014-03-10 17:47:34','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=365',0,'page','',0),(366,1,'2014-03-10 17:47:34','2014-03-10 17:47:34','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Pouring Acrylamide Gels for Manual Run</span></h3>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Hazardous materials:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nAcrylamide: neurotoxin\r\n\r\nTEMED: corrosive\r\n\r\nFor complete information, refer to the MSDS for each substance.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>PPE required:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nGloves: Nitrile\r\n\r\nEyewear\r\n\r\nLab Coat\r\n\r\nClosed toed shoes\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Precautions to observe:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nMix polyacrylamide under hood\r\n\r\nAvoid contact with skin/eyes\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;\">In case of contact:</span></strong></span>\r\n\r\nIf in contact with skin: remove clothing and use emergency shower or eye wash for 15 min\r\n\r\nCall EHS to clean up water in hallway\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;\">Procedure:</span></strong></span>\r\n\r\nPrepare plates (use the gel-pouring bench on the west side of the main lab)\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Cut bench paper large enough to cover the surface that you will be using.</li>\r\n	<li>Choose 1 short and 1 long plate per gel</li>\r\n	<li>Set plates on white, plastic tube racks.</li>\r\n	<li>Clean the inside of both plates with 95% ethanol and a Kimwipe</li>\r\n	<li>Clean with isopropanol and a kimwipe.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The plates should be completely free of smears or grease. After the isopropanol wash the glass will feel kind of slippery.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Wipe a small amount of Rain-X on the inside of the short plate ONLY.</li>\r\n	<li>Place spacers on each (long) side of the long plate.</li>\r\n	<li>Place the clean, Rain-Xed side of the short plate on top of the spacers, facing the long plate.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The bottom of the plates should be flush and spacers should be sandwiched inside the plates, aligned with the outer, long edges.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Use 2-4 binding clips to clip and hold the plates together.</li>\r\n	<li>Apply a casting boot to the bottom and sides of the plates removing clips as necessary.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Make sure the short plate is on top of the long plate and the hole to insert the syringe at the bottom of the boot is facing up.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preparation of polyacrylamide (must be done in the hood)</span>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>For each gel to be poured use the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>30ml 5% acrylamide (from 4 degree refrigerator)</li>\r\n	<li>90μl TEMED (in the hood)</li>\r\n	<li>90μl 10% APS (in 4 degree refrigerator)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Swirl gently in beaker.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Pouring polyacrylamide into ge</span>l\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Carefully draw ~35ml of the polyacrylamide solution into a plastic syringe avoiding air bubbles.</li>\r\n	<li>Insert syringe into the hole in the bottom of the casting boot.</li>\r\n	<li>Slowly depress plunger, allowing acrylamide to flow in between the plates.</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed until the acrylamide fills the space between the plates and begins to run out at the top of the short plate.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove syringe.</li>\r\n	<li>Plug hole in casting boot with modified pipette tip.</li>\r\n	<li>Insert comb, blunt side down, into the space at between the plates at the top of the gel.</li>\r\n	<li>Use 1-3 binding clips to secure the comb and the top of the plates together.</li>\r\n	<li>Wait ~20 minutes to allow adequate polymerization.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNotes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If you have trouble and have to discard the gel, POLYMERIZE the acrylamide first, before disposal. NEVER pour unpolymerized acrylamide down the drain.</li>\r\n	<li>Dispose of used bench paper after each use.</li>\r\n	<li>If supplies are running low, be sure to notify the ordering or stocks personnel.</li>\r\n	<li>Polymerized gels can be stored for future use by placing dampened (with water) paper towels over the top/bottom ends and covering the whole gel in saran wrap to avoid dehydration. Remove the casing boot prior to wrapping and storage.</li>\r\n</ul>','Acrylamide Gel Pour','','inherit','closed','open','','365-revision-v1','','','2014-03-10 17:47:34','2014-03-10 17:47:34','',365,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/365-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(367,1,'2014-03-10 17:51:46','2014-03-10 17:51:46','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Running Manual (not BaseStation) Acrylamide Gels</span></h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li> Put bottom tray into gel rig.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove clamps and wrap.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove boot and wash acrylamide off glass with normal water.</li>\r\n	<li>With gentle water running take out comb.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove any extra acrylamide and dry glass.</li>\r\n	<li>Take 2 black gel spacers (little and sponge-like)</li>\r\n	<li>Put plates into gel rig with short plate in back and sponges on side right on top of the plates (to prevent leaks).</li>\r\n	<li>Lock plates in with side clamps of gel rig. Clamp down very tightly.</li>\r\n	<li>Close drain on side.</li>\r\n	<li>Add 1X TBE to top, filling just a little below back knob just above liquid.</li>\r\n	<li>Fill bottom tray until little knobs next to plate are just above the liquid.</li>\r\n	<li>Prerun gel for 20 minutes at 1900V, 50W.</li>\r\n	<li>For 10ul PCR reactions, add 1:1 loading dye (so 10ul of loading dye). Put the dye in a tray and use a multi-channel pipet. Pour the extra back into the dye container.</li>\r\n	<li>Heat plate for 3 minutes at 95°C using Fisher hotplate and put weight on top.</li>\r\n	<li>The ladder (often use 400bp) is in 4°C fridge and it needs to be heated to 95°C for 2 minutes.</li>\r\n	<li>With a syringe, rinse the urea out of top of gel.</li>\r\n	<li>Put comb (teeth down) back into gel until teeth have entered acrylamide but not too deeply.</li>\r\n	<li>Add 3 ul of sample to each well using an 8 channel pipettor if possible.</li>\r\n	<li>Attach power leads and run at 1900V, 50W until dye front is near bottom.</li>\r\n	<li>Turn off power and open drain to remove buffer from top chamber.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove glass plates from gel rig.</li>\r\n	<li>Push spacer on right out a little bit and take a spatula to carefully open plate and remove smaller plate. Set it aside.</li>\r\n	<li>Put 0.8 grams of agarose into 30 ml nanopure water.</li>\r\n	<li>In a 50ml conical tube, add 25ml of nanopure water and 0.5ul of SYBR Green.</li>\r\n	<li>Pour SYBR Green/water solution into melted agarose flask. [alternatively add 50ml nanopure to 0.8g agarose and microwave; add 0.5ul of SYBR Green]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Mix together and pour over gel. Smooth solution out over gel with hands quickly.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Let it stain for ~10 minutes and then wipe plate with Kimwipe to remove any acrylamide from bottom and sides of plate so acrylamide won’t fall in Flourimager.</li>\r\n	<li>Put into Flourimager with combs facing towards you.</li>\r\n	<li>In flourimager program: Templates -&gt; Acryl top -&gt; name scan something</li>\r\n	<li>After scanning, clean gel off plate with a paper towel.</li>\r\n	<li>Use Sigma cleaner and a sponge to clean plates.</li>\r\n	<li>Rinse 1X with regular water and 1X with dI water. Can reuse 1X TBE until it turns blue.</li>\r\n</ol>','Running Acrylamide','','publish','closed','open','','running-acrylamide','','','2014-03-10 17:51:59','2014-03-10 17:51:59','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=367',0,'page','',0),(368,1,'2014-03-10 17:51:46','2014-03-10 17:51:46','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"> Running Manual (not BaseStation) Acrylamide Gels</span></h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li> Put bottom tray into gel rig.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove clamps and wrap.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove boot and wash acrylamide off glass with normal water.</li>\r\n	<li>With gentle water running take out comb.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove any extra acrylamide and dry glass.</li>\r\n	<li>Take 2 black gel spacers (little and sponge-like)</li>\r\n	<li>Put plates into gel rig with short plate in back and sponges on side right on top of the plates (to prevent leaks).</li>\r\n	<li>Lock plates in with side clamps of gel rig. Clamp down very tightly.</li>\r\n	<li>Close drain on side.</li>\r\n	<li>Add 1X TBE to top, filling just a little below back knob just above liquid.</li>\r\n	<li>Fill bottom tray